<title>Using Temporal Coherence to Build Models of Animals</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff">

<!-- ***********************************************************   
                  PAPER TITLE, ABSTRACT AND BIB INFO
****************************************************************//-->
<br>
<h1 align="center">&nbsp;&quot;Using Temporal Coherence to Build Models of Animals&quot;</h1>
<div align="center">
  <table border="0" width="800" cellpadding="5">
    <tr>
      <td><a href="../animals.pdf"><img border="0" 
src="animals_cover.gif" ></a></td>
      <td>
      <!-- *** Paper Abstract ***//-->

        <font SIZE="2">
        <p style="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0">
This paper describes a system that can build appearance models of 
animals automatically from a video sequence of the relevant animal 
with no explicit supervisory information. The video sequence need not have any form of special background. Animals are modelled as a 2D kinematic chain of rectangular segments, where the number of segments and the topology of the chain are
unknown.  The system detects possible segments, clusters segments whose appearance is coherent over time, and then builds a spatial model of such segment clusters. The resulting representation of the spatial configuration of the animal in each frame can be seen either as a track   --- in which case the system described should be viewed as a generalized tracker, that is capable of modelling objects while tracking them --- or as the source of an appearance model which can be used to build detectors for the particular animal. This is because knowing a video sequence is temporally coherent --- i.e. that a particular animal is present through the sequence --- is a strong supervisory signal. The method is shown to be successful as a tracker on video sequences of real scenes showing three different animals.  For the same reason it is successful as a tracker, the method results in detectors that can be used to find each animal fairly reliably within the Corel collection of images.  
    </p>
        <br>
        <br>
        </font>
        
        <!-- ***Paper Citation//-->
        <p> Ramanan, D., Forsyth, D. A.&nbsp;&quot;<b>Using Temporal Coherence to Build Models of Animals.</b>&quot; <i>Intl. Conf. on Computer Vision</i> (ICCV), Nice, France, Oct 2003 <a href="../animals.pdf">[pdf]</a>
        </p>

	<p> Ramanan, D., Forsyth, D. A., and Barnard, K.&nbsp;&quot;<b>Building Models of Animals from Video.</b>&quot; <i>IEEE Pattern Analysis and Machine Intelligence </i> (PAMI), Aug 2006 <a href="../animals_journal_draft.pdf">[pdf]</a>
        </p>

        <!-- ***Paper Links//-->
        <p align="center" >
	<a href="../../talks/animals_talk.pdf"> Talk Slides </a>
